<Base title="Primary sources library" compactHeader={true} toc={toc}>
  <p class="ar-title" lang="ar" dir="rtl">مكتبة المصادر</p>
  <h2>Primary sources library</h2>
  <p class="summary">A starter library of classical scholarly citations on the topics this site covers. Each entry names the scholar, the work, and where the cited position appears, with a brief excerpt or paraphrase. The aim is to give readers a foothold for going to the sources themselves rather than to substitute for them. Contributions and corrections are welcome via the GitHub issues link in the footer.</p>

  <p class="standards">Verification standard: every citation here points to a specific named work. Where the excerpt is verbatim from a recognised English translation, that is noted. Where it is an English paraphrase of an Arabic passage, the Arabic source is named and a reader who reads Arabic can verify directly. We do not invent attributions; we do not paraphrase as if it were a quote.</p>

  <h3 id="bidah">On the category of <em>bidʿah</em></h3>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Shāfiʿī</strong> (d. 204 AH) — narrated by al-Bayhaqī in <em>Manāqib al-Shāfiʿī</em></p>
    <p>"Innovations are of two kinds: praiseworthy innovation and blameworthy innovation. What agrees with the Sunnah is praiseworthy, and what opposes it is blameworthy" (<em>al-bidʿatu bidʿatān: bidʿatun maḥmūdah wa-bidʿatun madhmūma</em>). This is the foundational text in classical Sunnī <em>uṣūl al-fiqh</em> for the categorical distinction between <em>bidʿa ḥasana</em> and <em>bidʿa ḍalāla</em>.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>ʿUmar ibn al-Khaṭṭāb</strong> — Bukhārī, <em>Ṣaḥīḥ al-Bukhārī</em>, "Kitāb Ṣalāt al-Tarāwīḥ"</p>
    <p>Reacting to seeing congregational tarāwīḥ — which the Prophet ﷺ had performed only briefly, then ceased to perform in congregation lest it be made obligatory — ʿUmar said: "<em>niʿmati l-bidʿatu hādhihi</em> — what an excellent innovation this is." This narration is the textual basis for the classical Sunnī position that the term <em>bidʿa</em> is not exclusively pejorative; ʿUmar's usage establishes that a new institutional practice can be praiseworthy.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Nawawī</strong> (d. 676 AH) — <em>Sharḥ Ṣaḥīḥ Muslim</em>, on the ḥadīth "every innovation is misguidance"</p>
    <p>Al-Nawawī's commentary on this ḥadīth is the standard classical Shāfiʿī treatment: the Prophet's ﷺ statement is general in form but specific in intended scope; what it intends is innovation that contradicts the Sharīʿah, not every new occasion or arrangement. Al-Nawawī divides bidʿa into five fiqh categories — <em>wājib</em> (e.g., codifying the Qurʾān), <em>mandūb</em> (e.g., founding madrasas), <em>mubāḥ</em>, <em>makrūh</em>, and <em>ḥarām</em> — under the principle that the legal status of the innovated act is determined by its content, not by the fact of its newness.</p>
  </div>

  <h3 id="mawlid">On the Mawlid</h3>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam Jalāl al-Dīn al-Suyūṭī</strong> (d. 911 AH) — <em>Ḥusn al-Maqṣid fī ʿAmal al-Mawlid</em></p>
    <p>The standard classical Sunnī treatise on the Mawlid. Al-Suyūṭī classes the Mawlid as a <em>bidʿa ḥasana</em> when it consists of recitation of Qurʾān, narration of the Prophet's ﷺ life, charity, and joy, by analogy with congregational tarāwīḥ — which ʿUmar himself called <em>niʿmati l-bidʿatu hādhihi</em>. Al-Suyūṭī states in <em>al-Ḥāwī li al-Fatāwī</em> (1/221): "In my opinion, the basis of the Mawlid, which is the gathering of people, reciting what has been made easy from the Qurʾān, narrating the Aḥādīth about the beginning of the matter of the Prophet ﷺ and the signs that occurred upon his birth, it is a good innovation that the person will be rewarded for." He cites Ibn Ḥajar al-ʿAsqalānī as a fellow endorser among the major early-15th-century Sunnī authorities.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Ibn Ḥajar al-Haytamī</strong> (d. 974 AH) — <em>al-Fatāwā al-Ḥadīthiyya</em></p>
    <p>Al-Haytamī, the leading Shāfiʿī muftī of late-Mamlūk Mecca, endorsed the same classification as al-Suyūṭī. Asked about the gatherings of Mawlid and Dhikr, he responded (<em>al-Fatāwā al-Ḥadīthiyyah</em>, p. 109): "Most of the gatherings of Mawlid and Dhikr that take place around us are based on virtue as they contain Ṣadaqah, Dhikr, and Ṣalawāt and Salām upon the Prophet ﷺ … Those who gather for goodness are also praised by Allāh, and He boasts about them to the angels. Tranquility descends upon them, and they are enveloped in mercy … As for the questioner's inquiry on whether gathering for permissible innovations is allowed, the answer is yes, it is allowed." He also wrote a full book defending the practice: <em>Itmām al-Niʿmah al-Kubrā ʿalā al-ʿĀlam bi Mawlid Sayyid Walad Ādam</em>.</p>
  </div>

  <h3 id="tawassul">On tawassul and istighātha</h3>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam Taqī al-Dīn al-Subkī</strong> (d. 756 AH) — <em>Shifāʾ al-Saqām fī Ziyārat Khayr al-Anām</em></p>
    <p>Al-Subkī's full-length defense of tawassul, istighātha, and ziyāra of the Prophet ﷺ, written specifically against the Ibn Taymiyya line of restriction. The work goes through every relevant ḥadīth, the linguistic categories, and the four-madhhab fatwa positions. This is the standard classical Sunnī reference on the topic.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Tirmidhī</strong>, <em>Sunan al-Tirmidhī</em> 3578 — the ḥadīth of the blind man</p>
    <p>The Prophet ﷺ taught a blind man a duʿāʾ that includes the words: "<em>allāhumma innī asʾaluka wa-atawajjahu ilayka bi-Nabiyyika Muḥammad — yā Muḥammad, innī atawajjahu bika ilā rabbī fī ḥājatī hādhihi li-tuqḍā lī</em>" — "O Allāh, I ask You and turn to You by Your Prophet Muḥammad. O Muḥammad, I turn through you to my Lord with this need of mine, that it might be granted." Al-Tirmidhī graded the ḥadīth <em>ḥasan ṣaḥīḥ gharīb</em>; al-Albānī also authenticated it. The wording is the foundational textual basis for tawassul through the Prophet's ﷺ rank.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>al-Ṭabarānī</strong> — <em>al-Muʿjam al-Kabīr</em>, narration of ʿUthmān ibn Ḥunayf</p>
    <p>ʿUthmān ibn Ḥunayf, the Companion who originally narrated the blind-man's duʿāʾ from the Prophet ﷺ, taught the same wording to a man with a need <em>after</em> the Prophet's ﷺ death — and the man's need was granted. This narration is the textual basis classical Sunnī scholars cite for the permissibility of tawassul through the Prophet ﷺ after his earthly life.</p>
  </div>

  <h3 id="ziyara">On visiting graves (ziyārat al-qubūr)</h3>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Nawawī</strong> (d. 676 AH) — <em>al-Adhkār</em>, "Bāb mā yaqūluhu zāʾir al-qubūr"</p>
    <p>The standard classical Shāfiʿī chapter on visiting graves, presenting the recommended decorum: the salām formula transmitted from the Prophet ﷺ ("<em>al-salāmu ʿalaykum dāra qawmin muʾminīn</em>"), recitation of Qurʾān whose reward is sent to the deceased, and the duʿāʾ for forgiveness. Al-Nawawī treats grave visitation as recommended (<em>mustaḥabb</em>) for both men and women within the conditions transmitted from the Salaf.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>The Prophet's ﷺ address at al-Baqīʿ</strong> — <em>Ṣaḥīḥ Muslim</em></p>
    <p>ʿĀʾisha (raḍiya Allāhu ʿanhā) narrated that the Prophet ﷺ would visit the graveyard of al-Baqīʿ and address its inhabitants: "<em>al-salāmu ʿalaykum dāra qawmin muʾminīn, wa-innā in shāʾa Allāhu bikum lāḥiqūn</em>" — "Peace be upon you, O abode of a believing people; and we will, if Allāh wills, join you." This narration establishes both the practice of visiting graves and the Sunnah formula for addressing the deceased.</p>
  </div>

  <h3 id="attributes">On the divine attributes (ʿaqīdah)</h3>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam Abū Jaʿfar al-Ṭaḥāwī</strong> (d. 321 AH) — <em>al-ʿAqīda al-Ṭaḥāwiyya</em></p>
    <p>The most widely-accepted Sunnī creedal text — used by Atharī, Ashʿarī, and Māturīdī scholars alike. The relevant passage on transcendence: Allāh is exalted above limits, ends, organs, and instruments; the six directions do not contain Him as they contain all created things. The work is short (~75 brief paragraphs) and is the natural starting point for any reader new to Sunnī ʿaqīdah.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Ibn ʿAsākir</strong> (d. 571 AH) — <em>Tabyīn Kadhib al-Muftarī fī mā Nusiba ilā al-Imām al-Ashʿarī</em></p>
    <p>The foundational Sunnī refutation of the claim that Imam al-Ashʿarī recanted his Ashʿarī positions late in life and returned to a literalist Atharī stance. Ibn ʿAsākir documents the transmission chains of al-Ashʿarī's students and the authentic reception of his kalām method through the classical period. The work is essential reading for understanding the Ashʿarī school's own account of its founding figure.</p>
  </div>

  <h3 id="kalam">On kalām</h3>

  <div class="entry">
    <p class="cite"><strong>Imam al-Ghazālī</strong> (d. 505 AH) — <em>Iḥyāʾ ʿUlūm al-Dīn</em></p>
    <p>Al-Ghazālī classifies kalām — systematic rational theology in defense of Islamic ʿaqīdah — as <em>farḍ kifāyah</em> (a communal obligation) in circumstances where philosophical and rationalist challenges arise and no qualified scholar has answered them. His treatment in the <em>Iḥyāʾ</em> addresses both the conditions under which kalām becomes obligatory and its limits; this is the classical Sunnī position that distinguishes defensive kalām from the speculative excesses that the early scholars criticized.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>How this library will grow</h3>

  <p>This is a starter list. Topics not yet covered here that a future expansion could include: the Caliphate and political ʿaqīdah, the conditions and ranks of <em>ijtihād</em>, the specific positions of the four madhāhib on contested fiqh questions, the Ashʿarī/Māturīdī differences, and the Salafī primary sources (Muḥammad ibn ʿAbd al-Wahhāb, Albānī, ibn Bāz) presented in their own words. To suggest an addition or flag a misattribution, open an issue on the project's GitHub repository (link in the footer).</p>
